_:ae18d32f4b772d788310a6d39e815425 a <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/E52_Time-span> ;
	<http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P78_is_identified_by> "He was one of the first foreign-educated Ethiopians who acted as a diplomat, secretary and interpreter.\nMǝrč̣ā Warqe received his education at the British missionary school of John Wilson in Bombay.\nIn 1849 he left India and founded a school in ʿAdwā together with his\nbrother Gäbru Wärqe. Later, Mǝrč̣ā Warqe became a follower of Tewodros II.\nHe played a crucial political role during the British military compaign led by Robert Cornelis Napier.\nMǝrč̣ā Warqe established contact between Robert Cornelis Napier and Yoḥannǝs IV,\nthus securing support for Yoḥannǝs IV after the downfall of Tewodros II.\nIn 1875 Mǝrč̣ā Warqe was an envoy of Yoḥannǝs IV in Cairo.\nIn 1884 he acted as a secretary of Yoḥannǝs IV, and in 1896 he served as\nan interpreter for Mangašā Yoḥannǝs.\n               " .
<https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS7019MercaWa> <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P4_has_time_span> _:ae18d32f4b772d788310a6d39e815425 ;
